A virtual machine (VM) is like having another computer inside your laptop that runs its own operating system.


AI developers use VMs to test models safely without messing up their main system.


You need software like VirtualBox or VMware Workstation to create and run VMs.


Running AI in a VM can require a lot of RAM, storage, and CPU power, so stronger laptops work better.


VMs help isolate environments, which is useful when working with different AI libraries and versions.



One downside is that VMs can be slower than running directly on your laptop, especially for heavy AI tasks.